<DOC><DOCNO> AP880522-0041 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-88 1600EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Turkey-Kurds     05-22 0189</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Turkey-Kurds,0193</SECOND><HEAD>Two Soldiers Killed In Clash With Terrorists</HEAD><DATELINE>KILIS, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Turkish soldiers and Kurdish guerrillasclashed in this township near the Syrian border in fighting thatleft two Turkish soldiers dead, state radio reported Sunday.   The radio, quoting Gaziantep governor Husnu Tuglu, said thesoldiers fought with a group of five or six guerrillas who tried toslip into Turkey from Syria around midnight Saturday.   It said the terrorists fled into Syria after the clash. It didnot identify the suspected affiliation of the guerrilla band.However, most guerrillas operating in the region are linked to theKurdish Labor Party which seeks to set up a Marxist state in partsof eastern and southeastern Turkey.   Turkish officials have refrained from publicly accusing Syria ofharboring and aiding Kurdish guerrillas and other groups hostile toTurkey. Privately, intelligence officials say that Kurdishinsurgents have base camps in Syria and Iraq.   Nearly 900 civilians and military personnel and an equal numberof Kurdish rebels have been killed since Kurdish guerrillas startedhit-and-run attacks in 1984. Ethnic Kurds make up about one-fifthof Turkey's population of 52 million.</TEXT></DOC>